TIPS FOR MANUAL DATASET OR CSV FILES HOW TO USE IN COLAB


You must upload the CSV file first.

CODE (always run in new cell) :-

from google.colab import files
uploaded = files.upload()


once done step 2.

Case 1: Two-Mode CSV (Personsâ€“Committees)

Suppose they give you: dataset.csv :- 

Replace this old block: :-

data = {
    "Person": ["P1", "P1", "P2", "P2", "P3", "P4", "P4"],
    "Committee": ["C1", "C2", "C1", "C3", "C2", "C2", "C3"]
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

with new block :-

df = pd.read_csv("dataset.csv")

Everything else stays exactly the same.


Case 2: One-Mode CSV (Edge List)

Suppose they give you: edges.csv

Replace:

edges = [
    ('A', 'B'), ('A', 'C'),
    ('B', 'C'), ('C', 'D'),
    ('D', 'E')
]

with

df = pd.read_csv("edges.csv")
edges = list(zip(df["Header 1 in csv file"], df["Header 2 in csv fil"]))

Everything else stays the same.


Case 3: CSV as Adjacency Matrix.


Replace:

adj_matrix = np.array([
    [0, 1, 1, 0],
    [1, 0, 1, 1],
    [1, 1, 0, 0],
    [0, 1, 0, 0]
])

with:

adj_matrix = pd.read_csv("adj.csv", header=None).values

Everything else stays the same.
